Data types in SQL: character, integral, non-integral, miscellaneous
	1. Character (2 types)
		CHAR(n)- predetermined length (Also called CHARACTER(n))
			- max. size: 2000 bytes
		VARCHAR2(n) - varying length (maximum size=n) (Also called CHARACTER VARYING(n))
			- varchar stores size of actual no of characters + fixed size to store length
			- max. size: 4000 bytes
			
	2. Integral (3 types)
		-SMALLINT
		-INTEGER
		-INT
		
	NOTE: SQL does not provide support for arbitrary length numbers like python, java etc..
	
	3. Non-Integral (Integral + fractional parts)
		NUMBER(Precision, Scale)
			precision - total number of significant digits
			scale - total number of digits allowed after decimal point
		Ex: NUMBER(3,1) (33.3)
		NOTE: if precision and scale are not specified, then there will be no changes needed to the original number (ex: 123.29 , NUMBER)
		Checking validity of a Number:
			Ex: 121.79 
				precision-scale=3,scale=2
				so, the formats with precision-scale>=3 and scale>=2 will make the number valid
				NUMBER(6,1), NUMBER(5,2) etc.. makes the given value valid
	            If scale for the given format is less, we round off the given number
				If precision-scale is less then it will result in error
				Ex: NUMBER(4,2) will give error
								
	4. Miscellaneos
		-DATE (DD-MON-YY) Ex: 02-JUN-17
			-Using DATE type has many advantages. It checks for the validity of date. Thats why it is not feasible to use varchar for date formats
		-TIMESTAMP (DD-MON-YY HR:MIN:SECONDS AM/PM) Ex: 02-JUN-19 18:30:378463 PM
			-precision upto 9 digits of a second
		-CLOB (Character Large Object) Storing large character based data which cannot be stored using VARCHAR2
		-BLOB (Binary Large Object) Storing large binary data like movies, images etc..
		
Operators : Arithmetic, logical, comparision
	1. Arithmetic: 
		+,-,*,/
	2. Comparison
		=,<>,>,<,>=,<=
		Range (BETWEEN <low> and <high>)
		List (IN (List of values))  (If IN clause has duplicates then database server will remove duplicates before executing query)
		Patterns (LIKE)
		NULL  (IS NULL)
	NOTE: Assignment and equality check operators, both are same (=) in SQL unline java(= assignment and ==equality check)
	3. Logical
		-And (returns true if both are true)
		-or (returns true if either is true)
		-not (returns true if condition is false)